<subSubSection pageId="11" pageNumber="462" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="11.[151,1437,1373,2010]" pageId="11" pageNumber="462">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,273,1373,1398]" pageId="11" pageNumber="462">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Male. In the group III key of 
<bibRefCitation author="Borgmeier" box="[604,806,1373,1398]" pageId="11" pageNumber="462" refString="Borgmeier, T. (1964) Revision of the North American phorid flies. Part II. The species of the genus Megaselia, subgenus Aphiochaeta. Studia Entomologica, 7, 257 - 416." type="journal article" year="1964">
Borgmeier (
<number box="[738,798,1373,1398]" pageId="11" pageNumber="462" value="1964.0">1964</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
, 
<taxonomicName box="[817,969,1373,1397]" class="Insecta" family="Phoridae" genus="Megaselia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="462" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="hoggorum">
<emphasis box="[817,969,1373,1397]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="462">M. hoggorum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
keys to 
<taxonomicName authority="Borgmeier" authorityName="Borgmeier" box="[1062,1361,1373,1398]" class="Insecta" family="Phoridae" genus="Megaselia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="462" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="spiniclasper">
<emphasis box="[1062,1236,1373,1397]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="462">M. spiniclasper</emphasis>
Borgmeier
</taxonomicName>
which it differs from noticeably and immediately in the structure of the genitalia. 
<taxonomicName box="[1005,1181,1409,1433]" class="Insecta" family="Phoridae" genus="Megaselia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="462" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="spiniclasper">
<emphasis box="[1005,1181,1409,1433]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="462">M. spiniclasper</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has on the left side of the epandrium a single, long, curved projection bearing a terminal bristle. 
<taxonomicName box="[1018,1174,1445,1469]" class="Insecta" family="Phoridae" genus="Megaselia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="462" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="hoggorum">
<emphasis box="[1018,1174,1445,1469]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="462">M. hoggorum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
bears two much more subtle, rounded ventral projections off corners of the epandrium (
<figureCitation box="[882,965,1481,1506]" captionStart="FIGURES 75 – 80" captionStartId="26.[151,264,1740,1763]" captionTargetBox="[165,1422,186,1719]" captionTargetId="figure@26.[150,1436,169,1732]" captionTargetPageId="26" captionText="FIGURES 75 – 80. Male genitalia, left lateral. 75. Megaselia hentschkeae. 76. Megaselia hoffmanorum. 77. Megaselia hoggorum. 78. Megaselia hoguei. 79. Megaselia isaacmajorum. 80. Megaselia kelleri" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/242986/files/figure.png" pageId="11" pageNumber="462">
Fig. 
<number box="[934,965,1482,1506]" pageId="11" pageNumber="462" value="77.0">77</number>
</figureCitation>
), which are similar to those of 
<taxonomicName authority="Brues" authorityName="Brues" class="Insecta" family="Phoridae" genus="Megaselia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="462" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="dilatata">
<emphasis box="[1311,1436,1481,1505]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="462">M. dilatata</emphasis>
Brues
</taxonomicName>
(which comes out later in the key). Upon examination of 
<typeStatus box="[912,960,1518,1542]" pageId="11" pageNumber="462">type</typeStatus>
material, it was found that although the external structures of the genitalia of 
<taxonomicName box="[567,719,1553,1577]" class="Insecta" family="Phoridae" genus="Megaselia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="462" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="hoggorum">
<emphasis box="[567,719,1553,1577]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="462">M. hoggorum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName box="[773,897,1553,1577]" class="Insecta" family="Phoridae" genus="Megaselia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="462" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="dilatata">
<emphasis box="[773,897,1553,1577]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="462">M. dilatata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
were similarly shaped, 
<taxonomicName box="[1163,1315,1553,1577]" class="Insecta" family="Phoridae" genus="Megaselia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="462" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="hoggorum">
<emphasis box="[1163,1315,1553,1577]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="462">M. hoggorum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
lacked the prominent and largely protruding phallus complex visible on all specimens of 
<taxonomicName box="[1095,1225,1589,1613]" class="Insecta" family="Phoridae" genus="Megaselia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="462" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="dilatata">
<emphasis box="[1095,1225,1589,1613]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="462">M. dilatata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Additionally, 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Phoridae" genus="Megaselia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="462" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="hoggorum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="462">M. hoggorum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has much stronger epandrial setation.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
